  <thing id="cDragoRide" name="Dragon Rider" description="{b}Special{/b}: Must have ridden a dragon\n\nThroughout Krynn&#146;s history, dragons and their riders have fought together as effective teams, helping to change or sway the tide of battle. Both metallic and chromatic dragons are intelligent and powerful foes, yet they are solitary creatures and not have the innate talent, as do wolves or lions, to join together to hunt their foes in packs. Battles among dragons are fought on a one-to-one basis, with tooth and claw and magic, and they have little need for strategy and tactics.\n\nHumans teach dragons how much more efficient they can be in battle by pairing with a skilled rider who can guide the dragon in flight, watch out for additional foes, and wield his own weapon. A dragon fighting together with a skilled rider is a deadly and implacable foe.\n\nDragon riders develop a strong bond with their mounts that allows the two to work together to protect each other, communicate without words, and combine their skills to be as effective as possible in battle." compset="ClassLevel" maxlimit="10">
    <fieldval field="cHitDice" value="8"/>
    <usesource source="DLCS"/>
    <tag group="ClassType" tag="Prestige"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="Prestige"/>
    <bootstrap thing="cHelpDrR"></bootstrap>
    <link linkage="helper" thing="cHelpDrR"/>
    <exprreq message="Base attack bonus +10 required."><![CDATA[child[Attack].field[tAtkBase].value >= 10]]></exprreq>
    <exprreq message="Handle Animal 8 ranks required."><![CDATA[#skillranks[kHandleAnm] >= 8]]></exprreq>
    <exprreq message="Ride 8 ranks required."><![CDATA[#skillranks[kRide] >= 8]]></exprreq>
    <exprreq message="Leadership required."><![CDATA[#hasfeat[fLeader] <> 0]]></exprreq>
    <exprreq message="Mounted Combat required."><![CDATA[#hasfeat[fMountCom] <> 0]]></exprreq>
    <exprreq message="Resist Dragonfear required."><![CDATA[#hasfeat[fResDFear] <> 0]]></exprreq>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cDrRDragCo" name="Dragon Cohort" description="At 1st level the dragon rider may use the Leadership feat to designate a dragon that he has previously ridden as his dragon cohort, limited by the dragon rider&apos;s leadership score and the dragon&apos;s ECL (see Table 2-15). A dragon rider counts a dragon&apos;s ECL as being 3 lower than its actual value and he cannot attract a cohort whose ECL is higher than his total levels (an exception to the rule that a cohort must be of a lower level). A dragon will not agree to serve anyone whose alignment opposes its own and either party may sever the relationship at any time. After severing, the mount loses any benefit it gained according to Table 2-16 at a rate of -1 per week. A dragon cohort ages but does not gain experience.\n\nMost dragon cohorts are of at least young age. Red and gold dragons tend to be amenable to the relationship by the time they are very young. Dragons older than adult age make poor cohorts, since they are unable or unwilling to bind themselves to a humanoid for an extended amount of time.\n\nIn order to gain all class benefits, the dragon must be able to bear his rider (one size larger and max light load greater than rider weight). This means that small riders can actually use their cohorts as mounts earlier than medium counterparts.\n\nTable 2-15: Dragon Cohorts\nDragon (age/size)                   Alignment                    ECL(includes -3 adj)\nWhite (young/M)                            CE                                          9\nWyvern (-/L)                                    N                                            9\nBlack (young/M)                            CE                                         10\nBrass (young/M)                           CG                                         11\nCopper (young/M)                         CG                                         12\nRed (very young/L)                       CE                                          12\nGold (very young/L)                      LG                                          13\nGreen (young/M)                           LE                                          13\nBlack (juvenile/M)                         CE                                          14\nBlue (young/M)                              LE                                           14\nBrass (juvenile/M)                        CG                                          14\nDragon Turtle (-/H)                        N                                            14\nWhite (juvenile/M)                        CE                                           14\nBronze (young/M)                         LG                                           15\nCopper (juvenile/M)                     CG                                           15\nSilver (young/M)                           LG                                            15\nRed (young/L)                               CE                                            16\nGold (young/L)                              LG                                            17\nGreen (juvenile/L)                        LE                                            17\nBlack (young adult/L)                 CE                                            18\nBlue (juvenile/L)                           LE                                            18\nBrass (young adult/L)                 CG                                           18\nWhite (young adult/L)                 CE                                            18\nBronze (juvenile/L)                      LG                                            19\nCopper (young adult/L)              CG                                            19\nSilver (juvenile/L)                         LG                                            19" compset="ClSpecial" summary="Use leadership to get dragon cohort, -3 to Dragon ECL, max level = your level." sortorder="1">
    <tag group="ClSpecWhen" tag="1"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpDrR"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cDrRDrCoEn" name="Dragon Cohort Enhancement" description="The dragon rider must spend a minimum of seven days training with his cohort before any benefits accrue. Thereafter, the dragon gains the advantages listed in Table 2-16, based on the Dragon Rider&apos;s level. The dragon gains no abilities other than those listed, though it is considered a bonded companion (for abilities and spells that affect bonded relationships).\n\nTable 2-16: Dragon Rider&apos;s Mount\nDragon Rider Level       Bonus HD      Natural Armor         Strength Adjustment\n            1-3                                 +2                       +2                                  +1\n            4-6                                 +4                       +4                                  +2\n            7-9                                 +6                       +6                                  +3\n             10                                 +8                       +8                                  +4\n\n{i}Dragon Rider Level:{/i} This refers to the character&apos;s dragon rider levels only. If the dragon suffers a level drain, treat the dragon as the mount of a lower level dragon rider.\n\n{i}Bonus HD:{/i} These are extra twelve sided (d12) Hit dice, each of which provides a Constitution modifier, as normal. Remember that extra Hit Dice also improve the dragon&apos;s base attack and save bonuses. A dragon&apos;s base attack bonus is equal to it&apos;s HD and it has all good saves. The dragon doesn&apos;t get any extra feats or skill points for bonus HD.\n\n{i}Natural Armor:{/i} The number listed here is an improvement to the dragon&apos;s existing natural armor bonus. It represents the preternatural toughness of a dragon rider&apos;s mount.\n\n{i}Strength Adjustment:{/i} Add this figure to the dragon&apos;s Strength score." compset="ClSpecial" summary="Dragon cohort gains bonus HD, natural armor, and Strength." sortorder="1">
    <tag group="ClSpecWhen" tag="1"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpDrR"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cDrRDrCoRe" name="Dragon Cohort Responsibilities" description="The dragon rider has a number of responsibilities to his mount.\n\nFirst, the dragon needs a suitable lair. The {i}Monster Manual{/i} provides information detailing typical lairs for the various dragon species. Dragons not provided with a suitable lair will certainly rebel against their riders.\n\nSecondly, the dragon must be provided with treasure to keep in its lair. A minimum hoard of 1,000 gp value per HD of the dragon is typical, with the actual makeup of the hoard depending on the type and personal preferences of the dragon. The dragon is not keeping treasure safe for its rider, the hoard belongs to the dragon, who will not part with it easily.\n\nFinally, and most important, the dragon must be treated with the respect that a creature of its intelligence, power, and stature commands. It is not a dumb beast to order around, nor is it merely a minion to command. Even lawful good dragons are willful creatures with their own desires and needs." compset="ClSpecial" summary="1: Provide Lair   2: Provide Hoard   3: Provide Respect." sortorder="1">
    <tag group="ClSpecWhen" tag="1"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpDrR"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cDrRMountA" name="Mounted Attack" description="A dragon rider can always attack on the same round as his dragon cohort, and is not required to make a ride check to do so." compset="ClSpecial" summary="Attack with mount, no ride check required." sortorder="1">
    <tag group="ClSpecWhen" tag="1"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpDrR"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Extra"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cDrRDFeat1" name="Dragon Feats" description="A dragon rider can grant his dragon cohort the full benefits of a bonus feat chosen from the following list: Cleave, Flyby Attack, Hover, Improved Initiative, Improved Sunder, Power Attack, Quicken Spell-Like Ability, Snatch, Strafing Breath, Weapon Focus, of WIngover\n\nThe bonus feat does not count against the dragon&apos;s normal feat capacity, though it must still meet any prerequisites noted in the feat description. The dragon rider must spend one week training with his dragon in order for it to recieve the bonus feat. \n\nA second feat is granted at 5th level, and a 3rd at 9th level." compset="ClSpecial" summary="Dragon cohort gains listed bonus feat from training with rider." sortorder="2">
