  <thing id="cNoble" name="Noble" description="Nobles are illustrious because of thier rank, title, or birth. They have the ability to use thier background, education, natural charm, and skills in social maneuvering to thier advantage in their day to day lives. An elven princess, the Lord of Palanthas, a dwarven thane are examples of the noble class. While the motivations and goals of such characters vary widely, each is capable of masking his true intentions behind the veil of etiquette, and of using his charm and wit to gain what he desires.\n\n{b}Adventures{/b}: Adventuring nobles might be abroad at the behest of their families or working for a more powerful lord, such as a prince or king. Nobles are also effective diplomats, military commanders and politicians. In rare cases, a noble rebels against his heritage and responsibilities to work toward different goals, while still practicing the skills of his class. Nobles feel a sense of responsibility for those in their company.\n\n{b}Characteristics{/b}: While nobles are trained to defend themselves and fight to protect those for whom they hold responsibility, the noble&#146;s true battlefields are the throne room, the counsel chamber, the parlor, and the hallways&#151;any place where people meet and interact. His tongue and charm are his most effective weapons. Nobles prefer civilized areas, where laws are in effect and a clear social structure is defined. They often enjoy the finer things in life, including expensive clothes and good food and drink. Even impoverished nobles attempt to appear at their best. Nobles abhor crude behavior and may chastise those who demonstrate a lack of good manners.\n\n{b}Alignment{/b}: Nobles tend toward lawful alignments, working within the rules for their own personal goals, whether good or evil.\n\n{b}Religion{/b}: Nobles revere any deity who matches their own moral alignment (good, evil, or neutral) and whose motivations and methods match theirs. Being leaders themselves, they often honor Kiri-Jolith, Gilean, and Sargonnas.\n\n{b}Background{/b}: Almost every society has an &#147;upper class.&#148; Noble characters are born with either wealth or long family lineage, usually both. Anyone raised in a life of privilege might be a noble, even if they are not termed nobility by society. Nobles may also gain rank and title by advantageous marriages.\n\n{b}Races{/b}: Many of Ansalon&#146;s races have a defined aristocracy, including human, elven, and dwarven cultures. Races with a shifting (or nonexistent) social structure, such as kender, gully dwarves, or minotaurs produce few (if any) nobles.\n\n{b}Other Classes{/b}: Nobles work well with those who are educated, such as Knights of Solamnia, wizards, clerics, and bards. Noble characters sometimes have difficulty adjusting to the crude or rough behavior of those who have received their education in the streets or from nature, such as rogues, barbarians, and rangers." compset="ClassLevel" maxlimit="20">
    <tag group="ClassType" tag="Normal"/>
    <bootstrap thing="cHelpNbl"></bootstrap>
    <link linkage="helper" thing="cHelpNbl"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNblCoord" name="Coordinate +1" description="A noble has a knack for getting people to work together. When the noble can aid others and give directions, he provides a bonus to the task at hand by making an aid another check. This bonus is in addition to the normal aid another bonus of +2, and it increases as the noble gains levels. Therefore, the noble provides a total +3 bonus at 4th level (+2 aid another bonus, +1 cooperation bonus), a +4 bonus at 8th level, and so on.\n\nThis ability can&#146;t be used to assist in combat." compset="ClSpecial">
    <tag group="ClSpecWhen" tag="4"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpNbl"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Extra"/>
    <eval phase="PostAttr" priority="1000"><![CDATA[
~ Get our level
      var level as number
      level = hero.child[cHelpNbl].field[cTotalLev].value

~ Calculate our bonus     
      var total as number
      if (level = 20) then
        total = 5
      elseif (level > 17) then
        total = 4
      elseif (level > 12) then
        total = 3
      elseif (level > 7) then
        total = 2
      elseif (level > 3) then
        total = 1      
      else
        total = 0
        endif

~ Set our name
      field[livename].text = "Coordinate +" & total & ""

~ Set our description
    var aid as number
    aid = total + 2
      field[xSumm].text = "Aid another bonus becomes +" & aid & " for non combat purposes."]]></eval>
    </thing>
